<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) (SLC 025)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(SLC 025)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We welcome the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> opportunity to provide written evidence to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Select Committ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inquiry into safety at level crossings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Office of Rail Regulation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (ORR) is the combined economic and safety regulator for Britain’s railways. Safety is our paramount priority. As an independent regulator, we play a pivotal role in ensuring the industry delivers a safe, effective and efficient system. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e have a range of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulatory tools to secure improvements in health and safety standards and to secure legal compliance with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> law. O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">RR’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strategic objectives include a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rive for a safer railway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">setting out our commitment to e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nforce the law and ensure that the industry de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">livers continuous improvement in the health and safety of passengers, the workforce and public, by achieving excellence in health and safety culture, management and risk control. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail and operators of heritage and light rail have explicit legal duties under the Health and Safety at Work etc. Act 1974 (HSWA) to manage risks arising from level crossings on their network. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our primary in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">terest in level crossings is to promote, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and where necessary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> enforce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">safe design, management and operation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in order to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduce the risks, have a positive effect on user behaviour and so reduce the num</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ber of fatal and serious incidents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">near </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">misses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Today trains are more frequent and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">travel at higher speeds, there is more road traffic, bigger farm machinery using</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> crossings, people living a faster pace of life and more pedestrians using electronic equipment that can distract them.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  There are around 8000 level crossings on the network, m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any of which connect communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We often </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">face calls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from within those communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for them to remain open even when a case for closure has been made.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reality </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can be summarised as follows:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">support the closure and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> removal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, ensuring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all risk assessments consider closure first;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> better</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk assessment by crossing operators so that:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 102.9pt; padding-left:5.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people understand the risks and controls;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 102.9pt; padding-left:5.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">competent people undertake them;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 102.9pt; padding-left:5.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">parties </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">collaborate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to consider risks and controls;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 102.9pt; padding-left:5.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk management plans are produced for each crossing;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 102.9pt; padding-left:5.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">behaviour of users and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">perception of risk is influenced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – injuries and fatalities at level crossings are largely to members of the public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li></ul></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.22pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to encourage innovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and new technologies in</span></li></ul><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 102.9pt; padding-left:5.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bridging and underpasses;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 102.9pt; padding-left:5.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossing design and fitment;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 102.9pt; padding-left:5.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">specific controls at each crossing – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">moving away from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> one-size-fits-all “types” of crossing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.22pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to oversee Network Rail’s ring-fenced spend to reduce level crossing risk in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the next 5 years; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.22pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to implement the Law Commission improvements to the law on level crossings.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We expect the rail industry to achieve all th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is, leading to reduced risk and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduced harm and a better performing network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with fewer delays caused by level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossing collisions or near misses. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have clear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">published</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> policies and strategies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">setting out this approach and our expectations. We also state that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">no new level crossings should be installed unless there are exceptional circumstances</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the three new automatic open crossings authorised on behalf of the Secretary of State for the extension of the Welsh Highland Light Railway to Porthmadog - a scheme supported and funded by the Welsh Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">having significant societal benefits)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> devote significan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">urces to level crossings work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – a dedicated level crossings team plus engineers who provide technical expertise, and inspection teams that all undertake </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> inspections and investigations across the count</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ry.   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e inspect the industry’s management of level crossings to check that legal safety requirements are being met. Where failings are found, we have enforcement powers that we use to ensure the crossing is made safe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and its management improved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We also ensure that the industry acts in response to known level crossing safety issues that are raised, including recommendations made by the Rail Accident Investigation Branch. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Additionally, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have a role in authorising Level Crossing Orders (on beh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">alf of the Secretary of State for Transport), and then inspecting against </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to ensure that the measures that are set out in the Order are actually in place and being complied with.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Under the law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Level Crossing Orders are not mandatory for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Likely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reasons for Orders being in place include a need to clarify the specific safety requirements at a crossing, to clearly define what the respective duties of the crossing operator and highway authority are, or in some cases as a mechanism through w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hich prescriptive provisions for a crossing set in a private Act or Order for a railway can be modified. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are approximately 6500 level crossings on Network </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s infrastructure of which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2000 currently have Orders in force.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Britain’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s mainline</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> railway remains amongst one of the safest in the European Union (EU) in terms of the number of unsafe events that have happened, and is the best in the EU at managing risks to passengers and at level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> However, every incident has the potential fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r significant human and economic loss and hence socio-political effects stretching beyond the railway industry. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">espite</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a long-term trend of decreasing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk and number of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incidents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at level crossing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, nine members of the public died on crossings in 2012-13</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">two</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pedestrians</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, two cyclists, four car occupants and one moped </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fatalities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">April</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and August</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">two</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pedestrian</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and two vehicle occupants)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We recognise that each death and injury is a tragedy for individuals and their friends and family. Our role is to use our powers and influence to make sure that people can cross the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">railway safely, driven by a commitment to see this risk properly control</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">led and to avoid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">harm. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">attention </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ven to level crossing safety by the Select Committee’s inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and the efforts of campaigners and families to draw attention to level crossing safety and raise awareness of the risks.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Are current safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">measures at level crossings adequate? How should they be improved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are not content with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> merely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dequate” safety measures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our Strategy is to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">strive for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">excellence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in risk man</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gement and control</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here is always </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">room </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for improvement.  Whilst thousands of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossings remain on the network there will be risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Areas for improvement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">better risk recognition and assessment, improved co-operation and collaboration and more innovation and use of new technologies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Level crossing risk control is a shared responsibility between the infrastructure manager, the train operating companies, Highway Authorities (HAs) and users of the crossing. Effective co-operation and collaboration between these parties is critical and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ch has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a role to play, although the contribution of each party to risk control will vary at each crossing, as will their level of understanding.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This is why it is important for Network Rail to conduct joint risk assessments with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">parties, leading </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">them towards closure as the first and preferred option to be explored.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail is legally required to undertake </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> assessments and we are inspecting their compliance this year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, including whether joint assessments have been undertaken where we think</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> appropriate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ORR </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wish</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to see more widespread co-operation and collaboration </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">between Network Rail and other parties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst there are some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">examples of effective relationships betw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">een Network Rail and local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> HAs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Road Rail Partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) and between Network Rail and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">individual train operating companies in relat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion to crossings on their route, we would like to see more collaborative working to improve safety.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Recognition and assessment of risk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">critical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and a key focus of our work with Network Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to see them </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improve their competence in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, given that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> they manage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the vast majority o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f level cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssings on the netw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ork (around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6500</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> recent recruitment of 106 level crossing managers, each res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ponsible for specified level crossings, has demonstrated a necessary focus on level crossing management </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on their part</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but we now need to ensure that this translates into effective risk assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">publish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">guidance on designing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> managing and operating level crossings which puts great emphasis on the importance of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">suitable and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sufficient</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk assessment and we expect Network Rail to follow this. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is also essential that safety arrangements at crossings are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> kept under review thr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ough regular re-assessment of risks at the crossing and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the arrangements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may need to change if the risk profile at the crossing changes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The programme of new overhead electrification on parts of the railway is one such change that should trigger re-assessm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent of risks and controls at crossings. Other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increases in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> traffic levels (either road or rail), different levels of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pedestrian</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> usage, different behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s observed (wearing of headphones, use of mobile phones) or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> industrial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> developments in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> area.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> As crossing risks are re-assessed, new innovative controls may have become available or existing ones may have become more practical and cheaper to install as technologies, techniques and societal expectations change. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ORR has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">range of risk perceptions and interest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to balance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in respect of level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in particular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the perception of the risk of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">travel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">versus road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (and how this reflects </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Highway Authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> allocat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their resources and determin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ation of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heir </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">priorities)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> concerns </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and convenience </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">users.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">In addition to bridges and underpasses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">what other cost-effective measures can be introduced to replace or improve safety at level crossings?</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bridges and underpasses are by no means the only measure that can be considered. There </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a range of options </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that can be applied to particular crossings, depending on the risk assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that crossing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Examples are:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Closure of the crossing and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">creati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">diversion of rights of way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> - for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> private crossings where the landowner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s rights</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> can be bought out by Network Rail. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any closure must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">minimis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the possible transfer of risk to other crossings or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">introduction of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">new risks such as increasing the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">likelihood of trespass</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as far as is possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li styl