 style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will give the maxi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">um risk reduction in the n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">xt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> control period</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a commitment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to reduce the risk of accidents at level crossings by 8%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail made a commitment during </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the current control period</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(to 31 March 2014) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to reduce the risk of accidents at level crossings by 25% through level crossing closures, renewals and upgrade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has reported that level crossing risk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduction is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">26.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (August 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which takes them beyond their target.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The number of level crossing closures in this control period has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">passed 700 and is for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cast to exceed the control period closure target of 750. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Is Network Rail giving sufficient priority to improving safety at level crossings?</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is not a straightforward answer to this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> question</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lthough Network Rail has many</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> future plans and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> measures in place to improve safety at level crossings, there can never be room for complacency and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they need to strive towards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">excellence in risk management.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This is particularly important as,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ccording to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the risk models used by the rail industry,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">still present nearly half of the potential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">catastrophic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">train accident </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on the railway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Additionally, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">precursor indicator model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (PIM)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">developed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the Railway Safety and Standards Board (RSSB) to help understand the underlying risks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that might result in a train accident</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shows that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> overall downward trend until early 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is now reversing following a series of recent incidents. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The nine level crossing fatalities in 2012-13 resulted in a 7% increase in the PIM measured level crossin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This increase follows two years of improvements. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This reinforces the fact that there can never be room for complacency and Network Rail should always strive for excellence in level crossing risk management. ORR will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">continue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to inspect and monito</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r Network </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to ensure that it delivers on both its control period commitments and its on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">going legal duties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> under HSWA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to reduce risks at level crossings so far as is reasonably practicable. In particular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">looking for improved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> quality of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">undertaken by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Network Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">working collaboratively with other parties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the efficient implementation of identified safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">measures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We will be monitoring the effect and the pace of improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and the appropriateness and timeliness of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">actions taken</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It should be noted that not all level crossing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">managed by Network Rail; those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that lie on network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> operated by heritage railways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, light rail and trams</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are manag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d by those operators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> directly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">know </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that there are around 200</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eritage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> railway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> operators </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with around 1500 to 1800 crossings across the total heritage network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fewer than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fifteen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> crossings on metro/light rail networks. ORR does not normally consider the intersections of tramways and highways to be level crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and expects them to be signalled and managed as highway junctions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">line speeds are slower</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on heritage and light rail network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s and therefore are not as high risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> incidents can still occur. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ORR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> nominated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> inspectors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">closely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heritage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">railways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, light rail and tram operators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to reduce safety risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Over the last two years ORR has inspected all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">automatic level crossings on heritage lines to ensure compliance with legal requirements and good practice.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This resulted in most of the crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> being upgraded to meet current standards, especially the visibility of the warning lights.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As with the main line railway ORR considers level crossings of all types on minor railways to be areas of continuing risk and as such the inspection of crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will remain a standing item of work for ORR with this sector of the rail industry.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 13.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Heritage Railway Association has recently published straightforward guidance for their members on how to set appropriate sightlines at crossings as a result of ORR inve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stigations that showed that there was considerable inconsistency and misunderstanding of this important risk control measure.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Is Government policy and regulatory action by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety at level crossings adequat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">e? What more should the Government and ORR do?</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ORR places significant priority on level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> balance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">allocati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">get</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> bas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s across the railway industry as a whole</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We believe that we are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">concentrating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the right areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in respect of level crossings – a focus on crossing closure, effective, collaborative risk assessments and innovative controls – with a target of reducing risk and harm.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our strategy</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for health and safety regulation aims to reduce har</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m, targeting zero fatalities and ever-decreasing health and safety risks and excellence in both asset management and operations, and in health and safety management and culture. We want to see the following results: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">management capability across the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">industry improves;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is a measurable reduction in risks;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is a measurable reduction in harm, and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is a reduced likelihood of multiple-fatality incidents.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our approach combines checking legal compliance with proactively pushing for excellence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in management. Our targeted inspections regime checks legal compliance in the every-day control of risks by businesses in the industry. Our activity is targeted in a way which is proportionate to risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reflecting our assessment of in which parts of the in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dustry, non-compliance and risk of harm is greatest.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In most cases we secure improvements in level crossing safety through evidence-based advice and encouragement to duty holders to improve their risk management.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We have regular dialogue with Network Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on how they can improve safety.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would like to see less need for ORR to take formal enforcement action in response to failures by duty holders to maintain health and safety on the railway. However,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> when necessary, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we use our formal powers to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">compliance with the law or deal with immediate risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since April 2008 we have issued 23 Improvement Notices and 3 Prohibition Notices in relation to level crossings. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n 2012/13 we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> concluded two successful prosecutions for serious breaches of safety at le</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vel crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ecently, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rown </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rosecution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ervice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> successfully prosecuted Network Rail and an individual signaller for a level crossing fatality at Moreton-on-Lugg caused by the barriers being raised before all trains had passed.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ORR’s policy is to work with RAIB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to help ensure that their reports and recommendations appropriately ident</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ify and address safety concerns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and that each </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recommendation is taken into consideration and acted on appropriately. RAIB has investigated 41 level c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rossing accidents and incidents in total.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How should the legislation governing level crossings be updated?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The “once in a generation” opportunity afforded by the Law Commission project to reform level crossings legislation (expected publication date 25 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">September 2013) should be taken</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and we will work with the Department for Transport (DfT) to implement the relevant recommendations as soon as possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uch of the legislation covering level crossings is significantly dated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some as far back as to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Victorian times</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">criptive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in places</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a view shared</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> across the rail industry. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consequently, the archaic nature of the provisions and wording in some of the legislation leads to practical difficulties in applying the legal requirements to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">modern day scenarios</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any of the prescriptive provisions are no longer relevant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have been overtaken by more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">up-to-date </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">safety controls and equipment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That is why in 200</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ORR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, in collaboration with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">approached the Law Commission to ask them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to include level crossings legislation in their tenth programme of law reform. We were successful</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we have been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> closely with the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Law Commissions for England and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ales and the Scottish Law Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">since 2008 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as they have developed the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ir proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to modern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se and simplify the law in this area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We understand that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Law Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will be publishing their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">joint </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">report and a draft level Crossings Bill and supporting regul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tions in September</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. ORR </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the main </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">principles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to move </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">away from out-dated, prescriptive legislation and place the management of level crossing risk firmly under a HSWA framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to introduce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> public law style duties for key parties to co-operate effectively in the management of crossings and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to introduce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> streamlined processes for the closure of crossings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some elements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the Law Commission proposals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will require careful implementation to ensure that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the right emphasis is placed on managing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and that opportunities to reduce burdens are taken</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. For</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> example, we would not want the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reliance (by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">operators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) on obtaining regulator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> approval </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arrangements set out on a piece of paper</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– akin to a Level Crossing Order </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to be perp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etuate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but overall we welcome the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> opportunity to reform the law i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> important area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and look forward to working with DfT on the detailed implementation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How should public awareness of safety at level crossings be improved?</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is always potential to improve public awareness of safety at level crossings.  Faster running trains, increasing road traffic, more pedestrians, a faster pace of life </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ongoing need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for people t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o cross the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> railway reinforce this.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">greatest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> contributor to level crossing risk is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">misuse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the crossing by users, some of which is deliberate and some of which arises from error and misunderstanding. Risk profiling work using the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> RSSB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">afety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">odel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> shows that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the risk of collisions between trains and road vehicles is greatest at certain types of crossings – automatic half barrier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (AHB)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, automatic open crossings, locally monitored </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(AOCL) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and user worked crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (UWC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  There are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around 450</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> AHBs in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the country and they contribute considerably to the risk. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The greatest proportion of the risk to pedestrians is at footpath crossings and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">such incidents often</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> result in pedestrian </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">injuries and deaths</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The causes mainly fall into the categories of user error, defective crossing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">controls </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(in terms of its sighting distance or other controls) or signaller error</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Based on reported </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">data, user worked crossings with telephones </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">misused</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ossing type (around 30%) where, for example, users fail to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">use the phone to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contact the signaller before or after using the crossing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or leave gates open</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We recognise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">however</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that some of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">what is classified as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> “misuse” arises because human behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nderstanding of the risk by crossing users</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has not been taken into account sufficiently in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossing design</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or maintenance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and so “misuse” by a user may not always be their fault</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or done intentionally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We will seek to change the industry’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">way of thinking about “misuse” as a category in future.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail has run media-focused campaigns highlighting the dangers of level crossings for several years and has worked with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> British Transport Police</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (BTP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> who operate mobile enforcement vans dep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">loyed to crossings with high levels of misuse. Network </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">working with BTP and local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> install</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> red light enforcement cameras at crossings in the next control period. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> RSSB </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> undertak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> research into human factors that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will help with the design of crossings to minimise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">user</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> error</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">past and current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">RSSB research</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has looked at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Network Rail’s level crossing risk management model, level c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rossing related traffic signals, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">signs and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">miniature warning lights at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossings.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The Government funded </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">earch on human failure at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossings</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">formed the basis of RSSB’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossing toolkit</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ORR produced its own guidance for users of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossings in 2011 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and is currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with Network Rail and the Heritage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Railway Association to produce joint guidance in this area.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consistent with our role to regulate safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at businesses that employ people, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we target our activity to crossings that are used </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by farm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> businesses, agricultural contractors,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> utility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">companies, d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elivery firms, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Our objective is to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those businesses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have taken appropriate ste</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s to ensure their empl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">yees </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">understand how to use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s safely. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If clarification of any of the points made above is required, or we can be of further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assistance to the inquiry, please do not hesitate to contact me.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.rail-reg.gov.uk/upload/pdf/orr-safety-risk-strategy.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.rail-reg.gov.uk/upload/pdf/orr-safety-risk-strategy.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.rssb.co.uk/SiteCollectionDocuments/pdf/reports/Research/T335_rb_final.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.rssb.co.uk/SiteCollectionDocuments/pdf/reports/Research/T335_rb_final.pdf</span></a><span style="fo